1
00:00:06,006 --> 00:00:08,883
["I've Been Feeling Something Lately"
by Goodside playing]

2
00:00:12,345 --> 00:00:14,055
[Devi] If my mom knew
I was out on a weekday,

3
00:00:14,139 --> 00:00:15,306
she'd ground me till summer.

4
00:00:15,890 --> 00:00:17,225
-Your mom scares me.
-[chuckles]

5
00:00:17,308 --> 00:00:19,519
That's why I didn't tell my mom
where I'm going today.

6
00:00:19,602 --> 00:00:22,856
Good, because I am definitely not allowed
to be on a date right now. [chuckles]

7
00:00:23,606 --> 00:00:25,275
Which this is, right?

8
00:00:25,358 --> 00:00:27,527
-Yeah, obviously.
-[both laugh]

9
00:00:27,610 --> 00:00:30,363
Okay, on three, say where your mom
thinks you are right now.

10
00:00:30,447 --> 00:00:31,740
One, two, three…

11
00:00:31,823 --> 00:00:32,866
[both] Debate practice.

12
00:00:32,949 --> 00:00:36,119
-Whoa! You do debate too?
-Only since the first grade.

13
00:00:36,202 --> 00:00:38,705
Huh. Then I guess you and I
have a little showdown coming up

14
00:00:38,788 --> 00:00:40,373
at the Valley Regional Debate Tournament.

15
00:00:40,457 --> 00:00:43,501
2V2 public forum.
I look forward to cross-firing you.

16
00:00:43,585 --> 00:00:44,961
[McEnroe] Oh, snap!

17
00:00:45,045 --> 00:00:47,839
That was the hottest thing
a guy had ever said to Devi.

18
00:00:47,922 --> 00:00:51,885
And yet, there was one little thing
that was still bothering her.

19
00:00:51,968 --> 00:00:54,095
Hey, so can I ask you a question?

20
00:00:55,680 --> 00:00:56,639
Why did you ghost me?

21
00:00:57,932 --> 00:00:59,934
Look, I'm sorry. That was shitty of me.

22
00:01:00,018 --> 00:01:02,729
But after that party,
I kinda started to wonder

23
00:01:02,812 --> 00:01:05,940
if I should really be hitting on a girl
who was just crying over another guy.

24
00:01:06,024 --> 00:01:07,984
Uh, I was only crying for,
like, six minutes.

25
00:01:08,068 --> 00:01:10,779
-[sighs]
-But I see your point.

26
00:01:11,488 --> 00:01:13,907
You should know though, I'm over Paxton.

27
00:01:14,407 --> 00:01:16,201
I actually like someone else.

28
00:01:16,284 --> 00:01:19,454
["I've Been Feeling Something Lately"
continues playing]

29
00:01:19,537 --> 00:01:22,332
♪ I see the look that's in your eyes
I've been feeling something lately ♪

30
00:01:22,415 --> 00:01:24,375
-It's me, right?
-Yeah.

31
00:01:24,459 --> 00:01:27,629
♪ I've been feeling something lately ♪

32
00:01:27,712 --> 00:01:31,007
♪ I've been feeling something lately ♪

33
00:01:31,091 --> 00:01:32,592
♪ I've been feeling something lately ♪

34
00:01:32,675 --> 00:01:34,427
[Eleanor] Good morning,
you beautiful bitches.

35
00:01:34,511 --> 00:01:36,304
Wow, someone's in a chipper mood.

36
00:01:36,387 --> 00:01:40,558
Yes, I am because a talent agent
just emailed me about auditioning for her.

37
00:01:40,642 --> 00:01:42,393
-Congrats!
-That's awesome!

38
00:01:42,477 --> 00:01:45,188
Thanks! Seems like the commercials I did
really showcased my craft.

39
00:01:45,271 --> 00:01:47,816
Do you need some privacy
on your Jolly Roger?

40
00:01:47,899 --> 00:01:50,527
Set your sails for Captain Joe's Blinds.

41
00:01:51,027 --> 00:01:52,737
Thar she blinds!

42
00:01:52,821 --> 00:01:53,905
All sales are final.

43
00:01:53,988 --> 00:01:55,615
Can anyone help me tape it this weekend?

44
00:01:55,698 --> 00:01:57,951
[exhales] Sorry, El. Devi and I
have our debate tournament.

45
00:01:58,034 --> 00:02:00,161
Mmm. That's okay. I'll have Trent do it.

46
00:02:00,245 --> 00:02:02,413
Wait. So, Devi, are you excited

47
00:02:02,497 --> 00:02:04,499
to go up against Des
at the tournament this weekend?

48
00:02:04,582 --> 00:02:05,959
That's kind of spicy, huh?

49
00:02:06,042 --> 00:02:07,919
I know, right? We're gonna go at it.

50
00:02:08,002 --> 00:02:09,337
And then, we're gonna go at it,

51
00:02:09,420 --> 00:02:11,214
for a couple of minutes
until our moms pick us up.

52
00:02:11,297 --> 00:02:12,632
Do they suspect anything yet?

53
00:02:12,715 --> 00:02:15,218
Nope. That's the best part
of our moms being friends.

54
00:02:15,301 --> 00:02:17,679
We've been hanging out for weeks,
and they don't have a clue.

55
00:02:17,762 --> 00:02:21,850
Ugh! There's nothing sexier
than a secret liaison dangereux.

56
00:02:21,933 --> 00:02:26,354
[McEnroe] Little did they know, there was
another liaison dangereux in their midst,

57
00:02:26,437 --> 00:02:28,940
who were finally ready to go publique.

58
00:02:29,023 --> 00:02:31,442
There is something
that Aneesa and I would like to announce.

59
00:02:32,026 --> 00:02:33,278
We are together. [chuckles]

60
00:02:33,361 --> 00:02:36,698
What? How? When? Why?
Well, I know why. You guys are both hot.

61
00:02:36,781 --> 00:02:39,617
[laughs] Well, we kinda kissed
a while ago.

62
00:02:39,701 --> 00:02:40,743
You did?

63
00:02:40,827 --> 00:02:42,370
Yeah. We both had crushes in secret,

64
00:02:42,453 --> 00:02:44,455
but decided to make it official
at the coffeehouse.

65
00:02:44,539 --> 00:02:46,374
Holy crap, you guys. This is so exciting.

66
00:02:46,457 --> 00:02:47,458
[chuckles]

67
00:02:48,293 --> 00:02:50,086
-[Eleanor] Ah!
-[school bell ringing]

68
00:02:51,004 --> 00:02:55,049
-Hey, so what should we do tonight?
-I don't know. Hook up in your garage?

69
00:02:55,133 --> 00:02:58,178
Yeah, but we always do that.
Don't you get bored doing the same thing?

70
00:02:58,261 --> 00:03:00,346
I mean, what if we mix it up a little?

71
00:03:00,430 --> 00:03:02,640
Like, what if we went
to an art gallery or something?

72
00:03:02,724 --> 00:03:03,933
Would we get drunk before?

73
00:03:04,017 --> 00:03:06,269
Oh my God, that's such a good idea.

74
00:03:07,020 --> 00:03:09,230
Never mind. Let's just meet at my place.

75
00:03:09,314 --> 00:03:12,442
You should write movies, Paxton.
You're, like, so hilarious.

76
00:03:12,525 --> 00:03:14,360
[chuckles, kisses]

77
00:03:18,364 --> 00:03:20,575
Look at us, we're offish.

78
00:03:20,658 --> 00:03:22,619
Yo, Sherman Oaks,
hot couple alert. [chuckles]

79
00:03:22,702 --> 00:03:26,122
I know. Watch out, school,
Aneeola is here.

80
00:03:27,332 --> 00:03:29,042
Hmm. That sounds like a body part.

81
00:03:29,125 --> 00:03:30,668
[gasps] What about Fabees?

82
00:03:31,377 --> 00:03:32,837
No, that sounds like Febreze.

83
00:03:32,921 --> 00:03:34,923
How about just Fabiola and Aneesa?

84
00:03:35,632 --> 00:03:37,592
-[school bell ringing]
-[Aneesa] Oh.

85
00:03:38,468 --> 00:03:41,387
-Um, were you going for a hug or a kiss?
-I don't know. What were you doing?

86
00:03:41,471 --> 00:03:44,682
Like, are we PDA people or not?
Or like what's our goodbye ritual?

87
00:03:44,766 --> 00:03:47,644
-You know what, let's not overthink this.
-Yeah.

88
00:03:48,144 --> 00:03:48,978
Uh--

89
00:03:50,438 --> 00:03:51,314
[kisses]

90
00:03:52,440 --> 00:03:54,359
-I'll see you later!
-Yep. Yep. Sorry.

91
00:03:54,859 --> 00:03:57,737
[Rhyah] Des, Devi! Dinner in five!

92
00:03:59,197 --> 00:04:01,491
Hmm? Hey! Are you nuts?

93
00:04:01,574 --> 00:04:02,867
What if our moms catch us?

94
00:04:02,951 --> 00:04:04,953
How are we supposed to make out
if we're decapitated?

95
00:04:05,036 --> 00:04:06,913
-Maybe they'll bury our heads together?
-[laughs]

96
00:04:06,996 --> 00:04:08,414
[phone chimes]

97
00:04:08,498 --> 00:04:11,376
[Devi] "Easy practice sesh
at Sherman Oaks High"?

98
00:04:11,459 --> 00:04:15,088
Hey, are you calling our debate tournament
an easy practice sesh?

99
00:04:15,171 --> 00:04:17,632
Oh. Um, sorry. That's just how they put it
on the team calendar.

100
00:04:17,715 --> 00:04:20,426
Wait, so you guys think
you're gonna just show up and destroy us

101
00:04:20,510 --> 00:04:22,804
because you're
from a fancy private school?

102
00:04:22,887 --> 00:04:26,808
No. I mean, do we think
we have a good chance at winning?

103
00:04:26,891 --> 00:04:29,435
Yeah, but only because we always do.

104
00:04:29,519 --> 00:04:30,728
We've come close a few times.

105
00:04:30,812 --> 00:04:33,773
Well, that's because we usually send
our freshmen to compete against you.

106
00:04:33,856 --> 00:04:35,275
You do? Huh.

107
00:04:35,358 --> 00:04:37,360
I guess that's why we've never met before

108
00:04:37,443 --> 00:04:39,821
and why I thought everyone
at your school was strangely small.

109
00:04:39,904 --> 00:04:42,365
[laughs] But this time,
we're bringing our senior squad.

110
00:04:42,448 --> 00:04:43,449
So you and I can hang out.

111
00:04:44,993 --> 00:04:46,160
Wait, are you mad?

112
00:04:46,244 --> 00:04:47,912
I'm not trying to be insulting.

113
00:04:47,996 --> 00:04:49,956
It's just Hartman Hill
is nationally ranked,

114
00:04:50,039 --> 00:04:51,791
and we mostly compete against colleges.

115
00:04:51,874 --> 00:04:54,669
So what? Our school's
had four people audition for The Voice.

116
00:04:54,752 --> 00:04:56,087
And only two of them are now dead.

117
00:04:56,713 --> 00:04:58,339
Look, we have an unfair advantage.

118
00:04:58,423 --> 00:05:00,425
Our school just has
more resources than yours.

119
00:05:00,508 --> 00:05:03,803
The real problem is how underfunded
the public school system is.

120
00:05:03,886 --> 00:05:06,389
[scoffs] My school's doing just fine,
thank you.

121
00:05:06,472 --> 00:05:08,599
Look, I really didn't mean to offend you.

122
00:05:08,683 --> 00:05:10,268
Uh-- Well, I'm not offended.

123
00:05:10,351 --> 00:05:11,352
You should be offended

124
00:05:11,436 --> 00:05:14,063
by how badly you're gonna get crushed
at tomorrow's tournament.

125
00:05:14,814 --> 00:05:16,858
Okay. I look forward to it.

126
00:05:16,941 --> 00:05:17,817
Hmm.

127
00:05:19,110 --> 00:05:20,987
[Manish] Kamala, you're gonna love this.

128
00:05:21,654 --> 00:05:24,198
It says sexy 'cause, you know.

129
00:05:24,282 --> 00:05:25,742
[scoffs] There's my label maker

130
00:05:25,825 --> 00:05:28,161
and what's left
of my expensive label tape,

131
00:05:28,244 --> 00:05:30,288
but yes, you are very sexy.

132
00:05:30,371 --> 00:05:32,040
-Mmm. [kisses]
-[chuckles]

133
00:05:32,123 --> 00:05:33,166
What's all this gear?

134
00:05:33,249 --> 00:05:36,085
You got tape. You got trash bags.
What, you burying a body?

135
00:05:36,169 --> 00:05:38,546
Am I dating a future true crime star?

136
00:05:38,629 --> 00:05:40,923
No, I told my aunt
that I would help organize

137
00:05:41,007 --> 00:05:42,258
some of my grandmother's things.

138
00:05:42,342 --> 00:05:44,969
Yesterday, a pile of her boxes
from India toppled over

139
00:05:45,053 --> 00:05:47,096
and trapped her
for like 12 hours. [laughs]

140
00:05:47,180 --> 00:05:50,892
Well, don't worry, she's fine. She said
it was the best sleep she's had in years.

141
00:05:50,975 --> 00:05:52,852
I'd ask you to come, but you know.

142
00:05:52,935 --> 00:05:54,562
Yeah. Granny hates me.

143
00:05:54,645 --> 00:05:55,772
I get it. No worries.

144
00:05:55,855 --> 00:05:58,816
I have to judge a debate tournament
at the school today anyways,

145
00:05:58,900 --> 00:06:01,319
and those kids hate me slightly less.

146
00:06:01,402 --> 00:06:04,113
Mmm, sounds like we both have
thrilling Saturdays lined up.

147
00:06:04,197 --> 00:06:05,698
Yeah, why are we so boring?

148
00:06:05,782 --> 00:06:09,952
You know what? We should make up
for it tomorrow with a little bit of…

149
00:06:10,453 --> 00:06:11,746
[laughs]

150
00:06:12,580 --> 00:06:15,708
[Devi] And when I said that we were gonna
destroy Hartman Hill, Des laughed.

151
00:06:15,792 --> 00:06:18,544
Ergo, he thinks he's gonna win.
So we have to beat them.

152
00:06:18,628 --> 00:06:21,214
Although, I'd rather you not entangle
my academic pursuits

153
00:06:21,297 --> 00:06:22,799
in whatever kink this is for you,

154
00:06:22,882 --> 00:06:25,843
I'm gonna have to side with your
Love Island-looking boyfriend on this one.

155
00:06:25,927 --> 00:06:27,845
-Hartman Hill's gonna crush us.
-What?

156
00:06:27,929 --> 00:06:31,349
Yeah. I heard that their new coach
is the computer that won Jeopardy.

157
00:06:31,432 --> 00:06:33,142
Ben, since when do you just give up?

158
00:06:33,226 --> 00:06:36,229
Look, I'm trying not to get so hung up
on what other people are doing.

159
00:06:36,312 --> 00:06:38,398
Whatever.
We still have to try to beat them.

160
00:06:38,481 --> 00:06:41,984
How? Hartman Hill has LexisNexis Premium.
That means no commercials.

161
00:06:42,068 --> 00:06:44,445
Yeah. The only periodical
we have in our library

162
00:06:44,529 --> 00:06:45,947
is a free neighborhood paper.

163
00:06:46,030 --> 00:06:47,323
Sherman Oaks Tootler.

164
00:06:47,407 --> 00:06:50,368
The one that always arrives soaked
no matter what the weather is?

165
00:06:50,451 --> 00:06:53,704
Yep. This one from December's headline
is about a guy named Pete Flume

166
00:06:53,788 --> 00:06:56,416
who put up so many Christmas lights,
it blacked out his neighborhood.

167
00:06:56,499 --> 00:06:57,625
Hard-hitting stuff.

168
00:06:59,001 --> 00:07:01,546
Mr. Flume says, "It is my sacrosanct duty

169
00:07:01,629 --> 00:07:03,756
to infuse my neighborhood
with Christmas cheer."

170
00:07:03,840 --> 00:07:07,927
"And yes, that starts with a 20-foot-tall,
topless Mrs. Claus."

171
00:07:08,010 --> 00:07:10,096
Mmm. That should help us in the debate.

172
00:07:11,889 --> 00:07:13,766
[Mr. Shapiro] Organized debate

173
00:07:14,434 --> 00:07:18,896
can be traced all the way back
to the bosom of democracy.

174
00:07:18,980 --> 00:07:20,064
[laughing] He said bosom.

175
00:07:20,148 --> 00:07:22,066
There, philosophers and politicians

176
00:07:22,150 --> 00:07:25,027
would joust not with swords
but with their tongues.

177
00:07:25,111 --> 00:07:26,529
[laughs] He said tongues.

178
00:07:26,612 --> 00:07:32,326
And they would assemble for such debates
atop a hill known as the Pnyx.

179
00:07:32,410 --> 00:07:34,912
-[scoffs] He said--
-Okay, let's get this tournament going.

180
00:07:34,996 --> 00:07:38,207
Teams, you can see your room assignments
on the board. Good luck.

181
00:07:38,291 --> 00:07:41,711
And, Eric, you're not even in debate.
You should be in Saturday detention. Go.

182
00:07:41,794 --> 00:07:43,254
[sighs disappointedly]

183
00:07:46,132 --> 00:07:48,968
So, looks like we're
on opposite sides of the bracket.

184
00:07:49,051 --> 00:07:51,679
I guess we'll have to wait till the finals
to squash you ding-dongs.

185
00:07:51,762 --> 00:07:55,099
It'd be awesome if you made the finals.
We'll see how things go.

186
00:07:55,683 --> 00:07:57,477
I'm telling you how it'll go.

187
00:07:57,560 --> 00:07:59,395
Badly for you, goodly for me.

188
00:08:00,021 --> 00:08:02,106
But we'll still make out later, right?

189
00:08:02,815 --> 00:08:05,193
Stop trying to flirt with me.
We're mortal enemies today.

190
00:08:06,319 --> 00:08:08,529
-And yes, we can make out later.
-[laughs]

191
00:08:08,613 --> 00:08:11,866
Resolved, that performance-enhancing drugs
should be allowed in sports.

192
00:08:11,949 --> 00:08:14,577
Let's see what
the human body can do, baby.

193
00:08:14,660 --> 00:08:16,204
[upbeat music playing]

194
00:08:16,287 --> 00:08:19,999
It's clear that two-day shipping
is a very real threat to our society.

195
00:08:21,417 --> 00:08:26,380
So for the sake of our children,
we must do more vertical farming.

196
00:08:29,008 --> 00:08:31,886
[Trent] All right. Camera, ready. Action.

197
00:08:31,969 --> 00:08:34,514
I'm Eleanor Wong, and I'm 5'5",

198
00:08:34,597 --> 00:08:37,433
and I'll be doing Jennifer Lopez's speech
from Hustlers.

199
00:08:37,517 --> 00:08:39,393
-[Trent] Cut.
-[Eleanor] What do you mean, "cut"?

200
00:08:39,477 --> 00:08:40,811
I haven't even started.

201
00:08:40,895 --> 00:08:42,980
Sorry, I just feel
like it's missing something.

202
00:08:43,064 --> 00:08:44,482
Yeah, the whole monologue.

203
00:08:44,565 --> 00:08:47,235
No, that's not it. I'm worried
it's not gonna pop, you know?

204
00:08:47,318 --> 00:08:49,779
You need to be memorable
if this agent is gonna sign you.

205
00:08:49,862 --> 00:08:52,657
Is that why you brought a stripper pole?

206
00:08:52,740 --> 00:08:54,784
She's not even stripping
during the speech!

207
00:08:54,867 --> 00:08:57,578
-[Trent] I'm just trying to get levels.
-Sorry I dragged you here.

208
00:08:57,662 --> 00:08:58,955
Thought this would be more fun.

209
00:08:59,038 --> 00:09:01,999
Oh, I'm having fun.
I love watching people fight.

210
00:09:02,083 --> 00:09:04,794
-I'm a big UFC fan.
-[Trent] Let me explain my vision, okay?

211
00:09:04,877 --> 00:09:07,630
Babe, I'm just talking about
some subtle ambiance. Let me show you.

212
00:09:07,713 --> 00:09:09,840
Imagine doing your monologue,

213
00:09:09,924 --> 00:09:12,260
ripping those lines straight out
of your mouth hole.

214
00:09:12,343 --> 00:09:15,721
And just as your speech
climaxes super hard,

215
00:09:16,430 --> 00:09:17,473
this happens.

216
00:09:17,557 --> 00:09:19,058
[fireworks bursting, whistling]

217
00:09:19,141 --> 00:09:20,601
[Eleanor] Are you kidding me?

218
00:09:20,685 --> 00:09:22,186
Oh shit. I'm so sorry!

219
00:09:22,270 --> 00:09:25,147
The guy behind Baskin-Robbins assured me
these were the ones for pussies.

220
00:09:26,274 --> 00:09:27,817
-Eleanor! Wait!
-[Eleanor sobbing]

221
00:09:27,900 --> 00:09:29,944
[fire blazing]

222
00:09:30,027 --> 00:09:31,779
[Paxton] Oh shit.

223
00:09:32,947 --> 00:09:37,827
And we have our finalists!
Congrats to Sherman Oaks and Hartman Hill.

224
00:09:37,910 --> 00:09:39,662
[students cheering and applauding]

225
00:09:39,745 --> 00:09:41,038
And to the other teams,

226
00:09:41,122 --> 00:09:44,542
just remember there is no such thing
as losing, only learning.

227
00:09:44,625 --> 00:09:48,462
I've actually lost every competition
I've ever entered.

228
00:09:48,546 --> 00:09:49,797
[Ben] Hey, David.

229
00:09:49,880 --> 00:09:51,465
Don't be insufferable about this,

230
00:09:51,549 --> 00:09:53,718
but you may have been right
to think that we can win.

231
00:09:53,801 --> 00:09:55,928
Yeah, I know, right? We've been on fire.

232
00:09:56,012 --> 00:09:58,472
I mean, aside from
their beautifully tailored blazers,

233
00:09:58,556 --> 00:10:00,975
what do they have that we don't?
Absolutely no--

234
00:10:01,058 --> 00:10:04,854
A team of paralegals
and a fancy-looking omniscient computer.

235
00:10:04,937 --> 00:10:08,441
That's the computer that won Jeopardy.
We're so screwed!

236
00:10:08,524 --> 00:10:10,735
Okay, let's get to our final topic.

237
00:10:10,818 --> 00:10:13,988
Is the privatization
of outer space a just cause?

238
00:10:14,071 --> 00:10:17,783
Sherman Oaks, you won the coin toss.
Which side will you argue?

239
00:10:17,867 --> 00:10:19,744
[McEnroe] Aw, shit. Which one's easier?

240
00:10:20,536 --> 00:10:22,121
Look at them, so comfortable.

241
00:10:22,705 --> 00:10:24,206
Pits as dry as the Sahara.

242
00:10:24,790 --> 00:10:26,834
Is this a trap? What do we do?

243
00:10:26,917 --> 00:10:28,336
Uh, affirmative.

244
00:10:28,419 --> 00:10:30,421
Hartman Hill, you will argue the negative.

245
00:10:30,504 --> 00:10:31,672
[fire alarm sounding]

246
00:10:31,756 --> 00:10:35,551
Uh, unless the school burns down.
Everybody out, single file.

247
00:10:35,635 --> 00:10:38,304
[Mr. Shapiro] Okay. Very quickly,
but respect each other's bodies.

248
00:10:39,889 --> 00:10:42,016
Okay, I'm assuming this goes in the trash?

249
00:10:42,099 --> 00:10:44,935
-No, that's a definite keeper.
-Mami, you got to get rid of some things.

250
00:10:45,019 --> 00:10:47,563
You've only lived here a year
and have more things than Devi and I.

251
00:10:47,647 --> 00:10:50,858
I can't help that I have an eye
for incredible treasures.

252
00:10:50,941 --> 00:10:52,943
Like this bag of wrapping paper scraps?

253
00:10:53,027 --> 00:10:55,988
That's the perfect shape if I wanted
to give someone a straw as a gift.

254
00:10:56,072 --> 00:10:57,990
Kamala, you should take
your grandmother inside,

255
00:10:58,074 --> 00:10:59,617
and put away things from the keep pile.

256
00:10:59,700 --> 00:11:02,078
Rhyah and I will stay out here
and continue sorting.

257
00:11:02,161 --> 00:11:03,746
[Kamala] Okay. Come, Pati.

258
00:11:04,455 --> 00:11:05,998
[sighs] Okay.

259
00:11:06,082 --> 00:11:09,168
Oh. What's this wheelchair?

260
00:11:09,752 --> 00:11:13,172
Um, that was actually Devi's.

261
00:11:13,255 --> 00:11:14,090
What?

262
00:11:14,882 --> 00:11:15,716
What happened?

263
00:11:17,718 --> 00:11:20,262
[sighs] Oh, well, um…

264
00:11:20,930 --> 00:11:23,182
When Mohan died,
it was really hard on Devi,

265
00:11:23,265 --> 00:11:26,352
and, um, this really wild thing happened

266
00:11:26,435 --> 00:11:29,605
where she temporarily lost feeling
in her legs.

267
00:11:29,689 --> 00:11:32,400
Oh no! That must have been so scary.

268
00:11:32,483 --> 00:11:33,943
Hmm, yeah, it was terrifying.

269
00:11:34,026 --> 00:11:37,822
[inhales] Last couple of years have been
a bit of a roller-coaster ride for us.

270
00:11:38,406 --> 00:11:41,325
-[sighs] You wanna talk about it?
-I don't know.

271
00:11:41,409 --> 00:11:46,372
You know, she's… she's just been angry,
and she's acted out a lot.

272
00:11:46,455 --> 00:11:49,083
And she even got suspended from school.

273
00:11:49,166 --> 00:11:50,251
Oh God.

274
00:11:51,127 --> 00:11:53,421
Yeah, but she's doing so much better.

275
00:11:54,380 --> 00:11:56,424
I'm sorry you've had
such struggles, Nalini.

276
00:11:56,507 --> 00:11:58,134
I can't imagine how hard it's been.

277
00:11:58,217 --> 00:12:00,344
[sighs] Thank you.

278
00:12:00,428 --> 00:12:02,763
And Des has just always been so easy.

279
00:12:03,973 --> 00:12:07,268
[sighs] I need to remember
to feel gratitude about that.

280
00:12:08,352 --> 00:12:09,186
Thank you.

281
00:12:13,232 --> 00:12:16,110
Ugh! I can't believe my boyfriend
is an arsonist.

282
00:12:16,777 --> 00:12:18,738
This is actually good.
We needed a beat anyway.

283
00:12:18,821 --> 00:12:21,741
There is no way Hartman Hill's allowed
to have paralegals, right?

284
00:12:21,824 --> 00:12:24,994
I mean, there's nothing in the rule book
against it. So it's technically legal.

285
00:12:25,077 --> 00:12:25,995
[phone dings]

286
00:12:26,662 --> 00:12:28,873
[Des] Hey, congrats on getting
to the finals, killer!

287
00:12:28,956 --> 00:12:31,375
My team went on a matcha run.
Can I grab you something?

288
00:12:31,459 --> 00:12:33,085
Hartman Hill is getting matcha.

289
00:12:33,169 --> 00:12:35,296
They're so relaxed,
they need an energy boost?

290
00:12:35,379 --> 00:12:36,797
And he called you "killer."

291
00:12:36,881 --> 00:12:38,966
It's what my grandmother's
kickboxing coach calls her,

292
00:12:39,049 --> 00:12:40,468
and she does the class seated.

293
00:12:40,551 --> 00:12:43,179
[McEnroe] Devi knew
that Des was trying to be nice,

294
00:12:43,262 --> 00:12:46,474
but it was infuriating
how unthreatened he was.

295
00:12:46,557 --> 00:12:49,226
The only thing separating
his team from hers was money,

296
00:12:49,810 --> 00:12:53,022
which paid for professionals
to do all their research,

297
00:12:53,105 --> 00:12:56,942
research that was sitting
in the school completely unguarded.

298
00:12:57,026 --> 00:12:59,111
No, Devi, that's cheating.

299
00:12:59,695 --> 00:13:02,448
But then again,
weren't they kind of cheating?

300
00:13:02,531 --> 00:13:06,952
This was an unfair playing field,
and perhaps it was time to level it.

301
00:13:07,036 --> 00:13:11,165
-[Eleanor yelling indistinctly]
-Man, she is going off. You okay?

302
00:13:11,749 --> 00:13:14,502
No, I'm not okay. I'm thriving.

303
00:13:14,585 --> 00:13:17,296
What? But you guys are in a fight.

304
00:13:17,379 --> 00:13:19,089
Nah, that's just what El and I do.

305
00:13:19,173 --> 00:13:21,675
We rile each other up,
and then we love each other down.

306
00:13:21,759 --> 00:13:24,428
If you tried to dick tap me right now,
you'd probably break your hand.

307
00:13:24,512 --> 00:13:25,471
Okay.

308
00:13:25,554 --> 00:13:27,973
Honestly, being in a relationship
this passionate,

309
00:13:28,474 --> 00:13:30,267
it's like the best high I've ever had.

310
00:13:30,351 --> 00:13:32,978
And I've been struck
by lightning. [laughs]

311
00:13:33,062 --> 00:13:35,189
I don't know, man, seems like a lot.

312
00:13:35,272 --> 00:13:36,315
[Trent] Oh, you do you.

313
00:13:37,358 --> 00:13:40,569
Now, if you'll excuse me,
Daddy's gotta go get scolded.

314
00:13:40,653 --> 00:13:42,655
[curious music playing]

315
00:13:45,866 --> 00:13:47,868
[fire alarm sounding]

316
00:13:48,410 --> 00:13:49,245
[sighs]

317
00:13:49,328 --> 00:13:51,330
[music continues]

318
00:14:01,757 --> 00:14:04,176
Hey! Devi, what are you doing in here?

319
00:14:04,802 --> 00:14:07,388
Oh, um, I was just, uh…

320
00:14:07,471 --> 00:14:10,224
seeing if any students
needed to be saved from the fire.

321
00:14:11,141 --> 00:14:13,018
Nope. [laughs] All good.

322
00:14:13,519 --> 00:14:14,603
Let's debate, bro. [laughs]

323
00:14:14,687 --> 00:14:16,313
[upbeat music playing]

324
00:14:19,525 --> 00:14:21,193
Aneesa, what are you doing here?

325
00:14:21,277 --> 00:14:23,863
I'm here to be a good girlfriend.
Look, I made you a sign.

326
00:14:24,446 --> 00:14:26,448
Oh. [chuckles] Thank you.

327
00:14:26,532 --> 00:14:29,994
No, no, I hold it. This is what
girlfriends do at football games.

328
00:14:30,077 --> 00:14:30,953
Oh.

329
00:14:31,036 --> 00:14:32,413
So when do you go out there?

330
00:14:32,496 --> 00:14:34,164
I don't. I'm just an alternate.

331
00:14:34,248 --> 00:14:36,500
So I sit here
unless someone calls out sick.

332
00:14:37,167 --> 00:14:39,211
Oh. Okay.

333
00:14:39,295 --> 00:14:42,464
Cool. Guess I'll just sit over here then.

334
00:14:43,048 --> 00:14:44,758
[Des] Well, I definitely didn't move it.

335
00:14:44,842 --> 00:14:46,051
Hey, we're missing a binder.

336
00:14:46,135 --> 00:14:49,263
Uh, I didn't touch it.
It was probably the new paralegal.

337
00:14:49,346 --> 00:14:51,599
I saw her order
a Bloody Mary at breakfast.

338
00:14:54,727 --> 00:14:58,480
Tell you what, I think that fire
kind of ruined the flow of things.

339
00:14:58,564 --> 00:15:01,567
So in the interest of keeping things fair,

340
00:15:01,650 --> 00:15:04,653
I think Sherman Oaks and Hartman Hill
should switch sides.

341
00:15:04,737 --> 00:15:06,196
Uh-- Objection, Your Honor.

342
00:15:06,280 --> 00:15:08,449
To what? To fairness, Devi?

343
00:15:09,116 --> 00:15:10,367
Um, no.

344
00:15:10,951 --> 00:15:12,286
That's what I thought.

345
00:15:12,995 --> 00:15:13,829
Let's begin.

346
00:15:14,872 --> 00:15:17,082
Okay, now here's a box that's a keeper.

347
00:15:17,166 --> 00:15:20,836
Look at all these old photos
and several rolling pins,

348
00:15:20,920 --> 00:15:22,296
but mostly photos.

349
00:15:22,880 --> 00:15:24,715
Oh, look there's you.

350
00:15:24,798 --> 00:15:26,342
Oh, and Tata.

351
00:15:27,051 --> 00:15:28,928
This is when we used to have
ice cream Sundays,

352
00:15:29,011 --> 00:15:31,555
which was when all we would eat
on Sunday was ice cream.

353
00:15:31,639 --> 00:15:32,765
I always got very sick.

354
00:15:32,848 --> 00:15:36,894
I remember. I was the one who had
to feed you clear rasam the next day.

355
00:15:36,977 --> 00:15:40,648
[laughs] Oh, I miss Tata.
He was so much fun.

356
00:15:40,731 --> 00:15:43,525
Yes, sometimes a little too fun.

357
00:15:43,609 --> 00:15:45,277
I loved your grandfather,

358
00:15:45,361 --> 00:15:47,947
but he was more of a dreamer than a doer.

359
00:15:50,282 --> 00:15:51,116
How so?

360
00:15:51,200 --> 00:15:55,704
He never liked any job that he had,
so he frequently had no job at all.

361
00:15:55,788 --> 00:15:59,041
And I had to make what little
we did have stretch a long way.

362
00:15:59,124 --> 00:16:01,210
Why do you think I save all this stuff?

363
00:16:01,919 --> 00:16:03,295
Pati, I had no idea.

364
00:16:04,046 --> 00:16:07,800
But it does give a whole new meaning
to this shoebox filled with loose sporks.

365
00:16:08,384 --> 00:16:11,095
Kanna, this is what scares me
about Manish.

366
00:16:11,178 --> 00:16:14,682
That you will have to be a parent to him,
like I was to my husband.

367
00:16:14,765 --> 00:16:16,976
I look at Manish
with his high-top sneakers

368
00:16:17,059 --> 00:16:19,061
and sparkly men's earrings,

369
00:16:19,144 --> 00:16:20,646
and I don't see a grown-up.

370
00:16:20,729 --> 00:16:22,856
I don't see someone
who can make sacrifices

371
00:16:22,940 --> 00:16:24,316
for you and your family.

372
00:16:25,693 --> 00:16:28,570
Pati, I know you're trying to protect me.

373
00:16:29,321 --> 00:16:30,572
But Manish is not Tata.

374
00:16:30,656 --> 00:16:34,034
And one day,
I hope he'll get to prove that to you.

375
00:16:35,369 --> 00:16:38,872
And that's time.
Let's move on to closing statements.

376
00:16:38,956 --> 00:16:40,749
Hartman Hill, you're up first.

377
00:16:41,500 --> 00:16:43,752
Our planet
becomes less habitable by the day,

378
00:16:43,836 --> 00:16:46,797
so private space exploration
is imperative to human survival.

379
00:16:46,880 --> 00:16:49,883
As a local venture capitalist stated
in a recent LA Times op-ed,

380
00:16:49,967 --> 00:16:51,844
"It is our sacrosanct duty…"

381
00:16:51,927 --> 00:16:53,554
[laughs] He said stank doodie.

382
00:16:53,637 --> 00:16:55,597
Eric, go to detention!

383
00:16:56,181 --> 00:16:57,933
[McEnroe] Wait, Eric was right.

384
00:16:58,017 --> 00:16:59,685
Not about the stank part.

385
00:16:59,768 --> 00:17:01,979
Des did say "sacrosanct duty."

386
00:17:02,062 --> 00:17:04,231
Why did that phrase sound so familiar?

387
00:17:04,314 --> 00:17:06,734
"It is our sacrosanct duty
as private companies

388
00:17:06,817 --> 00:17:08,485
to ensure the future of our species."

389
00:17:08,569 --> 00:17:11,363
"So those beautiful twinkling lights
in the sky

390
00:17:11,447 --> 00:17:13,949
can still represent hope."

391
00:17:14,033 --> 00:17:15,909
-Thank you.
-[all applauding]

392
00:17:17,077 --> 00:17:18,787
Sherman Oaks, you're up.

393
00:17:19,788 --> 00:17:21,915
Before I begin, what was the name

394
00:17:21,999 --> 00:17:23,792
of the venture capitalist
who wrote that op-ed?

395
00:17:23,876 --> 00:17:26,045
Oh, uh, yeah, Peter Flume.

396
00:17:26,128 --> 00:17:29,048
-Hell yeah. I need the Tootler.
-What?

397
00:17:29,131 --> 00:17:30,507
[Devi] The Sherman Oaks Tootler.

398
00:17:31,383 --> 00:17:33,385
-I wrapped my sandwich in it.
-Oh my God.

399
00:17:37,431 --> 00:17:39,099
I'd like to introduce into evidence

400
00:17:39,183 --> 00:17:42,019
the December 9th edition
of the Sherman Oaks Tootler.

401
00:17:42,603 --> 00:17:45,439
Turns out your boy
is a resident of Sherman Oaks,

402
00:17:45,939 --> 00:17:48,484
and his mansion's pervy Christmas display

403
00:17:48,567 --> 00:17:52,821
was so big
that it cut power to a local hospital.

404
00:17:52,905 --> 00:17:53,947
[students murmuring]

405
00:17:54,031 --> 00:17:58,577
[Devi] My fellow humans, guys like this
don't care about anyone else.

406
00:17:58,660 --> 00:18:02,289
Privatization makes the world
a crappier, more unjust place.

407
00:18:02,372 --> 00:18:07,961
[scoffs] No matter if it's in
space exploration or in education.

408
00:18:08,670 --> 00:18:10,130
[all applauding]

409
00:18:10,214 --> 00:18:11,256
Let's go!

410
00:18:12,049 --> 00:18:14,093
Okay. It's unanimous.

411
00:18:14,176 --> 00:18:16,762
With that closing statement,
Sherman Oaks is the winner.

412
00:18:16,845 --> 00:18:18,472
-Yes!
-[all cheering]

413
00:18:18,555 --> 00:18:21,892
-[student] Way to go!
-[all applauding]

414
00:18:23,894 --> 00:18:27,898
And, Ms. Vishwakumar,
if you could just hang back for a second.

415
00:18:28,690 --> 00:18:29,525
Mmm.

416
00:18:30,859 --> 00:18:34,279
Amazing job, babe. You looked like
you could have subbed in at any moment.

417
00:18:34,363 --> 00:18:37,366
Well, I'm glad I didn't.
I hate public speaking.

418
00:18:37,449 --> 00:18:39,493
I don't know why
I signed up for debate. [laughs]

419
00:18:41,662 --> 00:18:44,289
Oh! Ahh! My incisors.

420
00:18:44,373 --> 00:18:46,708
Damn. What's going on with us?
Why are we so awkward?

421
00:18:46,792 --> 00:18:48,877
I don't know. I really like you.

422
00:18:48,961 --> 00:18:50,420
I really like you too.

423
00:18:50,504 --> 00:18:54,049
I think it's probably always weird
when you go from friends to girlfriends.

424
00:18:54,133 --> 00:18:56,426
But we'll get there.

425
00:18:56,510 --> 00:18:59,304
Yeah, in… in no time,
we're going to be PDAing so hard,

426
00:18:59,388 --> 00:19:00,722
people will be like, "Get a room."

427
00:19:00,806 --> 00:19:02,516
[both laugh]

428
00:19:04,685 --> 00:19:05,686
Congrats on the win.

429
00:19:06,603 --> 00:19:09,481
Hey, look what I found in the trash.

430
00:19:10,232 --> 00:19:12,776
Hartman Hill's missing binder.
It's weird, huh?

431
00:19:13,360 --> 00:19:14,862
[scoffs] Super weird.

432
00:19:15,487 --> 00:19:16,989
Why'd they throw it away?

433
00:19:17,072 --> 00:19:19,825
You know what,
rich people just don't value property

434
00:19:19,908 --> 00:19:21,034
the same way you and I do--

435
00:19:21,118 --> 00:19:23,036
Devi, stop it. I know you cheated.

436
00:19:24,037 --> 00:19:26,290
And the sad thing is,
you didn't even have to.

437
00:19:26,373 --> 00:19:30,085
Uh-- I did it in the name of justice.
Did you not see their paralegals?

438
00:19:30,169 --> 00:19:31,461
I'm basically Jean Valjean.

439
00:19:31,545 --> 00:19:33,714
Yeah, well,
then I'm a better singing Russell Crowe

440
00:19:33,797 --> 00:19:35,465
because now I gotta take you to prison,

441
00:19:35,549 --> 00:19:39,178
aka your house, aka the place
where everyone hates me already.

442
00:19:39,261 --> 00:19:41,972
So this is just fantastic.
Get your bag. Let's go.

443
00:19:46,560 --> 00:19:49,813
So, what are your plans after graduation?

444
00:19:50,397 --> 00:19:52,441
Oh, um, I hadn't really thought about it.

445
00:19:52,524 --> 00:19:55,235
I bet there'll be, like,
a graduation party that night,

446
00:19:55,319 --> 00:19:56,612
so I'll probably go to that.

447
00:19:57,571 --> 00:19:59,823
I meant, like,
do you want to go to college--

448
00:19:59,907 --> 00:20:00,991
Quiet on set, people!

449
00:20:01,074 --> 00:20:02,910
Eleanor and I have come to a compromise,

450
00:20:02,993 --> 00:20:04,828
which is that we think
Eleanor's way is best.

451
00:20:04,912 --> 00:20:09,082
All right, babe.
Lights, camera, cell phone.

452
00:20:09,750 --> 00:20:14,213
I'm Eleanor Wong. I'm 5'5",
and this is Jennifer Lopez in Hustlers.

453
00:20:15,047 --> 00:20:15,881
Look, baby.

454
00:20:16,465 --> 00:20:19,218
We gotta start thinking
like these Wall Street guys.

455
00:20:19,301 --> 00:20:21,053
You see what they did to this country?

456
00:20:21,136 --> 00:20:23,472
They stole from everybody.

457
00:20:23,555 --> 00:20:25,933
Hardworking people lost everything.

458
00:20:26,516 --> 00:20:29,102
You ever think about when they come
into the club?

459
00:20:29,186 --> 00:20:30,395
That's stolen money.

460
00:20:30,979 --> 00:20:31,855
Eff these guys.

461
00:20:31,939 --> 00:20:33,941
[cinematic music playing]

462
00:20:36,068 --> 00:20:36,944
Cut!

463
00:20:37,027 --> 00:20:39,404
-[clapping, laughing]
-[Eleanor squeals, laughs]

464
00:20:39,488 --> 00:20:42,616
You killed it, babe! These agents
are gonna sign the shit out of you.

465
00:20:42,699 --> 00:20:44,993
And I can't believe you used
my mom's stripper pole.

466
00:20:45,077 --> 00:20:47,287
It was perfect. Thank you for pushing me.

467
00:20:48,455 --> 00:20:49,331
You make me better.

468
00:20:49,414 --> 00:20:50,499
You make me better.

469
00:20:50,582 --> 00:20:51,583
[both chuckle]

470
00:20:58,799 --> 00:20:59,841
[knocking on door]

471
00:20:59,925 --> 00:21:01,551
-[Nirmala] Hold on.
-[Devi] Seriously?

472
00:21:01,635 --> 00:21:02,636
Oh boy.

473
00:21:03,262 --> 00:21:06,473
Manish? What a pleasant surprise
you did not clear with me beforehand.

474
00:21:06,556 --> 00:21:09,351
Yeah. Hello, everyone. Sorry to interrupt.
I'll just cut to the chase.

475
00:21:09,434 --> 00:21:12,062
I caught Devi cheating
in the debate tournament today.

476
00:21:12,980 --> 00:21:14,481
I'm… I'm sorry. She did what?

477
00:21:14,564 --> 00:21:16,024
Oh, that is serious.

478
00:21:16,942 --> 00:21:20,696
It seems like it's a family moment.
I'll just go back into the garage.

479
00:21:21,738 --> 00:21:23,782
Devi, how could you?

480
00:21:23,865 --> 00:21:26,451
So, what does this mean?
Is she suspended again?

481
00:21:26,535 --> 00:21:28,870
I decided not to inform the principal.

482
00:21:29,371 --> 00:21:31,748
Seems like something
you'd rather handle in-house.

483
00:21:32,708 --> 00:21:33,542
Thank you, Manish.

484
00:21:34,918 --> 00:21:36,420
-Up to your room.
-Okay.

485
00:21:36,503 --> 00:21:39,548
Couldn't you get into trouble
for not reporting this?

486
00:21:39,631 --> 00:21:41,967
Maybe, but I know how hard Devi works,

487
00:21:42,050 --> 00:21:45,804
and I don't want to mess up her future
because of one stupid mistake.

488
00:21:45,887 --> 00:21:49,516
Anyway, sorry about all this,
and I promise not to bother you again.

489
00:21:49,599 --> 00:21:51,226
Wait, please come inside.

490
00:21:52,394 --> 00:21:54,646
-Is this a trap?
-Please do it before she changes her mind.

491
00:21:54,730 --> 00:21:56,523
Okay. Whoa, you got a tight grip.

492
00:21:56,606 --> 00:21:57,858
[Nalini] Pardon me.

493
00:21:57,941 --> 00:21:59,401
Oh boy. Uh…

494
00:21:59,484 --> 00:22:01,361
Manish, I owe you an apology.

495
00:22:01,945 --> 00:22:05,365
I thought you were nothing more
than an immature, bumbling hooligan.

496
00:22:05,449 --> 00:22:08,160
-I mean, I'm a full-time teacher.
-Anyway, I was wrong.

497
00:22:08,660 --> 00:22:11,955
Despite what your haircut says about you,
you are a grown-up.

498
00:22:12,039 --> 00:22:15,459
You were tough on Devi today,
but you also protected her.

499
00:22:15,959 --> 00:22:17,377
That's what family does.

500
00:22:18,170 --> 00:22:20,922
So I'm happy for Kamala
to be with someone like you.

501
00:22:22,758 --> 00:22:25,677
Although, I would like you to learn
something more about your culture.

502
00:22:25,761 --> 00:22:28,347
Perhaps I can be your tutor.
Would you like that?

503
00:22:28,430 --> 00:22:30,724
He would love that.
Thank you, Pati. [chuckles]

504
00:22:30,807 --> 00:22:31,892
Good.

505
00:22:33,060 --> 00:22:34,936
[Des] Hey! Devi? Are you up there?

506
00:22:35,437 --> 00:22:37,647
Yeah. Come in.

507
00:22:39,149 --> 00:22:41,360
Hey, my mom asked me to bring takeout.

508
00:22:41,443 --> 00:22:44,196
While they were fighting
over spring rolls, I snuck upstairs.

509
00:22:44,279 --> 00:22:46,323
Damn. Well played, dude.

510
00:22:46,406 --> 00:22:49,159
If anyone deserves a "Damn.
Well played, dude," it's you.

511
00:22:49,242 --> 00:22:50,202
You clobbered us.

512
00:22:50,952 --> 00:22:52,329
Technically, yes.

513
00:22:53,246 --> 00:22:56,458
But I also may have cheated,
but in a way that didn't even help us,

514
00:22:56,541 --> 00:22:57,793
so you can't be that mad.

515
00:22:57,876 --> 00:22:59,127
Uh, you've lost me.

516
00:23:00,003 --> 00:23:03,799
-I'm the reason your binder went missing.
-Oh man. That was you?

517
00:23:03,882 --> 00:23:05,884
Parker fired one
of our paralegals for that.

518
00:23:05,967 --> 00:23:08,345
I'm sorry,
but how else are we supposed to compete

519
00:23:08,428 --> 00:23:11,056
with your paralegals
and the fricking Jeopardy computer?

520
00:23:12,474 --> 00:23:16,269
Yikes. Look, I'm not psyched
you stole our research, but frankly,

521
00:23:16,353 --> 00:23:19,773
I don't blame you guys for trying to give
yourselves an edge. That's what we do.

522
00:23:19,856 --> 00:23:23,819
Like, for instance,
we might take a normal desktop computer

523
00:23:23,902 --> 00:23:27,406
and put a screen saver on it
so it looks like the one from Jeopardy.

524
00:23:27,489 --> 00:23:29,991
No! I asked that computer
for an autograph.

525
00:23:30,075 --> 00:23:31,159
[laughs]

526
00:23:31,243 --> 00:23:32,494
Look, I'll be honest.

527
00:23:33,161 --> 00:23:35,205
-I'm intimidated by you.
-Hmm?

528
00:23:35,288 --> 00:23:39,000
I don't think I've ever dated someone
as smart as me or maybe even smarter.

529
00:23:39,084 --> 00:23:40,335
[chuckles]

530
00:23:40,919 --> 00:23:41,837
I think I like it.

531
00:23:42,712 --> 00:23:44,256
Well, I like it too.

532
00:23:45,006 --> 00:23:46,758
-Being smarter than you.
-[chuckles]

533
00:23:46,842 --> 00:23:49,219
[Nalini] Devi,
why am I hearing voices up there?

534
00:23:49,302 --> 00:23:51,388
You better not be listening to a podcast!

535
00:23:52,013 --> 00:23:53,807
Okay, you got to get out of here.

536
00:23:53,890 --> 00:23:57,185
But maybe you could throw
a spring roll up the stairs?

537
00:23:57,936 --> 00:23:59,020
You got it.

538
00:23:59,104 --> 00:24:02,065
♪ You used to shine so bright
But you soured ♪

539
00:24:02,149 --> 00:24:04,192
♪ At the taste of a bitter leaf ♪

540
00:24:04,276 --> 00:24:08,530
♪ Took it all out on me
But I see through you ♪

541
00:24:08,613 --> 00:24:11,992
♪ And you won't be causing me no grief
Anymore ♪

